    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-05-14T16:28:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-05-14T16:28:00-05:00" n="35"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d35">
                <head>35. Telegram From the Joint <gloss type="from">Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                    Commander in Chief, U.S. Naval Forces, Eastern Atlantic and Mediterranean
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HAJLJ1" type="to">Holloway</persName>), at
                        London<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d35fn1">Source: National Archives
                        and Records Administration, RG 218, <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                        Files: CCS 381 Lebanon (5–13–58) Sec. 1. Top Secret; Operational Immediate;
                        Noforn. Repeated to <gloss target="#t_USCINCEUR1">USCINCEUR</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCLANT1">CINCLANT</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_USNMR1"
                            >USNMR</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-05-14T17:28:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 14, 1958—5:28 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 941782. <gloss target="#t_USNMR1"
                        >USNMR</gloss> pass to <gloss target="#t_SACEUR1">SACEUR</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> governmental position: <list>
                            <label>a.</label>
                            <item>Command of combined forces used in Lebanon operations will be
                                United States.</item>
                            <label>b.</label>
                            <item>For both political and military reasons United States forces
                                should precede <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> forces into
                                Lebanon.</item>
                            <label>c.</label>
                            <item>These two points agreeable to State Dept and approved by <gloss
                                    target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>. British suggest detailed planning
                        should be done in Mediterranean and not in London.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
